data.description: We're happy to announce that our first blood drive of the semester on campus is scheduled on September 13th and 14th at the Yard on College Avenue. We feel great pride that Rutger's UBI is able to help in this beautiful drive hosted by Robert Wood Johnson Barnabas Health. Today, the country confronts new challenges that disrupt the blood supply. As concerns compound, blood centers nationwide are facing a decline in donor turnout, and donor eligibility misinformation. Yet the need for blood remains constant. We need youth like you to donate and save a life!  Donors will receive a $5 coffee gift card, a jersey mikes sub, a t-shirt, and a chance to win 1 out of 4 $25 WaWa Gift cards!

data.description: Please sign up here: https://forms.gle/LXoA5Ym2qZ65SBcY9   As a volunteer, you'll have the opportunity to be a part of the exciting and fast-paced action that is dragon boat racing. You'll also get to experience the energy and excitement of the festival event atmosphere and be a part of a vibrant community of dragon boat enthusiasts. Volunteers will be needed to help with various tasks in ensuring the safety and smooth operations of the event through the various outlined tasks:    Volunteer Roles Need:   Boat Marshalls- will be on the dock assisting paddlers with getting in and out of the boats. This position should be filled by people who are comfortable around water. Results Runners- will be posting the results from the Timing Officials at the Registration Headquarters. This position requires neat handwriting. Team Marshalls- will assist the Marshalling Manager in ensuring that all teams are ready to load into boats at the correct time to maintain smooth running of the raves. Crowd Control- will ensure one-way flow traffic from the Marshaling Area after boats are unloaded.   All Volunteers will receive:    Volunteer Hours (if applicable) Free shirt Free Lunch and Drinks Opportunity to ride in a dragon boat Opportunity to make new friends and have fun  Basic Event Info:  Location: Mercer County Park, east of the Marina at 334 S Post Rd, West Windsor Twp, NJ 08691 Date: Saturday, 9/16/23 Time: Pickups starts at 6am, Event is 7am-5pm   Sign-ups will be first-come first-serve. Form closes 9/14/23 Ride Groups will be created after sign-ups close.   Expect to spend most of the day with us. Hats and Sunscreen are recommended
data.name: Dragon Boat Volunteering

data.description: Hello Student Veterans Organization (SVO) Members and Friends! We hope you had an amazing summer break, and we're excited to welcome you back for an exciting new academic year. It's time to kick off Fall 2023 with a bang, and what better way to do it than coming together for our first General Meeting! At this meeting, we'll:   Get to Know Each Other: Whether you're a returning member or brand new to the SVO, we're all about making connections and building a supportive community. Let's introduce ourselves and hear your stories!   Upcoming Events: Discover the fantastic events and activities we have planned for this semester, including recreational activities, networking opportunities, workshops, and community service projects.   Executive Updates: Hear from our dedicated Executive Board members about their roles and what they've been working on to make this year a success.   Open Discussion: Have ideas or suggestions? We're all ears! This is your chance to share your thoughts on what you'd like to see from your SVO this year.   We want this to be a space where you feel welcomed and inspired, and where your voice matters. So, whether you're a student veteran or a supporter of veterans' causes, join us on September 26th at 7:00 PM. Let's make this year unforgettable together!
data.name: First SVO General Meeting!

They will be oriented on how to properly welcome new leadership and retain talent, review the organizational financial process, how to cope with vacancies, change, and conflict resolution to name a few. data.description: Celebrate the end of the academic year by joining Douglass staff, the Voorhees Choir, and fellow students for the annual Sacred Path Ceremony. One of Douglass' oldest traditions, the Sacred Path ceremony recognizes student achievement and fosters Douglass's unique community. Join your fellow Douglass classmates, alumnae, friends, and family as each class is honored with a symbol representing the different class years. After you receive your charm, head to the ceremonial fires on the sacred path to make a wish!  Students should show their pride by wearing their class year colors (first years wear white, sophomores wear pink, juniors wear red, and seniors wear black). Every student will receive a charm, a token representing her class. All Douglass students, family, faculty, and alumnae are welcome! Refreshments will be provided at Ludwig immediately following the ceremony.  *Students in Knowledge & Power will receive 2 points towards their Douglass event requirements*
data.name: Sacred Path 2024
data.organizationName: Traditional Events at Douglass Residential College - DRC
